event: response.output_text.done
data: {"type":"response.output_text.done","content_index":0,"item_id":"msg_0336d5a3d8fdf9990169e478e0d9908193a044cf1f290d227a","logprobs":[],"output_index":1,"sequence_number":509,"text":"### Monte Hall (3-door) problem — logic explanation\n\n**Setup**\n- 3 doors: one has a car, two have goats.\n- You first pick 1 door.\n- The host (who knows where the car is) then opens **one** of the other two doors, always showing a goat.\n- You’re offered a choice: **stay** with your original door or **switch** to the remaining unopened door.\n\n---\n\n## Key logic\n### 1) Your first pick already determines where the car “was” relative to your choice\nAt the moment you pick:\n- Probability your chosen door has the car = **1/3**\n- Probability the car is behind one of the other two doors = **2/3**\n\nSo we can think in two cases:\n\n### 2) Case analysis\n\n#### Case A: You initially picked the car (prob = 1/3)\n- The host opens a goat door among the other two.\n- The only unopened other door is a goat.\n- If you **switch**, you lose.\n- If you **stay**, you win.\n\n#### Case B: You initially picked a goat (prob = 2/3)\n- The car is behind one of the other two doors.\n- The host must open a goat door (and won’t open the car door).\n- That means the **only remaining unopened** door must be the car.\n- If you **switch**, you win.\n- If you **stay**, you lose.\n\n---\n\n## Conclusion\n- Switching wins in Case B, which happens with probability **2/3**.\n- Staying wins in Case A, which happens with probability **1/3**.\n\n### Therefore:\n- **Stay:** \\(1/3\\)\n- **Switch:** \\(2/3\\)\n\nThe reason this isn’t “50/50 after one door opens” is that the host’s action is **not random**; it’s constrained by knowing where the car is, which preserves the original \\(2/3\\) advantage of the “not chosen” doors."}

event: response.content_part.done
data: {"type":"response.content_part.done","content_index":0,"item_id":"msg_0336d5a3d8fdf9990169e478e0d9908193a044cf1f290d227a","output_index":1,"part":{"type":"output_text","annotations":[],"logprobs":[],"text":"### Monte Hall (3-door) problem — logic explanation\n\n**Setup**\n- 3 doors: one has a car, two have goats.\n- You first pick 1 door.\n- The host (who knows where the car is) then opens **one** of the other two doors, always showing a goat.\n- You’re offered a choice: **stay** with your original door or **switch** to the remaining unopened door.\n\n---\n\n## Key logic\n### 1) Your first pick already determines where the car “was” relative to your choice\nAt the moment you pick:\n- Probability your chosen door has the car = **1/3**\n- Probability the car is behind one of the other two doors = **2/3**\n\nSo we can think in two cases:\n\n### 2) Case analysis\n\n#### Case A: You initially picked the car (prob = 1/3)\n- The host opens a goat door among the other two.\n- The only unopened other door is a goat.\n- If you **switch**, you lose.\n- If you **stay**, you win.\n\n#### Case B: You initially picked a goat (prob = 2/3)\n- The car is behind one of the other two doors.\n- The host must open a goat door (and won’t open the car door).\n- That means the **only remaining unopened** door must be the car.\n- If you **switch**, you win.\n- If you **stay**, you lose.\n\n---\n\n## Conclusion\n- Switching wins in Case B, which happens with probability **2/3**.\n- Staying wins in Case A, which happens with probability **1/3**.\n\n### Therefore:\n- **Stay:** \\(1/3\\)\n- **Switch:** \\(2/3\\)\n\nThe reason this isn’t “50/50 after one door opens” is that the host’s action is **not random**; it’s constrained by knowing where the car is, which preserves the original \\(2/3\\) advantage of the “not chosen” doors."},"sequence_number":510}

event: response.output_item.done
data: {"type":"response.output_item.done","item":{"id":"msg_0336d5a3d8fdf9990169e478e0d9908193a044cf1f290d227a","type":"message","status":"completed","content":[{"type":"output_text","annotations":[],"logprobs":[],"text":"### Monte Hall (3-door) problem — logic explanation\n\n**Setup**\n- 3 doors: one has a car, two have goats.\n- You first pick 1 door.\n- The host (who knows where the car is) then opens **one** of the other two doors, always showing a goat.\n- You’re offered a choice: **stay** with your original door or **switch** to the remaining unopened door.\n\n---\n\n## Key logic\n### 1) Your first pick already determines where the car “was” relative to your choice\nAt the moment you pick:\n- Probability your chosen door has the car = **1/3**\n- Probability the car is behind one of the other two doors = **2/3**\n\nSo we can think in two cases:\n\n### 2) Case analysis\n\n#### Case A: You initially picked the car (prob = 1/3)\n- The host opens a goat door among the other two.\n- The only unopened other door is a goat.\n- If you **switch**, you lose.\n- If you **stay**, you win.\n\n#### Case B: You initially picked a goat (prob = 2/3)\n- The car is behind one of the other two doors.\n- The host must open a goat door (and won’t open the car door).\n- That means the **only remaining unopened** door must be the car.\n- If you **switch**, you win.\n- If you **stay**, you lose.\n\n---\n\n## Conclusion\n- Switching wins in Case B, which happens with probability **2/3**.\n- Staying wins in Case A, which happens with probability **1/3**.\n\n### Therefore:\n- **Stay:** \\(1/3\\)\n- **Switch:** \\(2/3\\)\n\nThe reason this isn’t “50/50 after one door opens” is that the host’s action is **not random**; it’s constrained by knowing where the car is, which preserves the original \\(2/3\\) advantage of the “not chosen” doors."}],"phase":"final_answer","role":"assistant"},"output_index":1,"sequence_number":511}

